      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Barbarians at the Digital Gate'' (Sept. 19), which described how pop-up ads and other interruptions were angering computer users:</p>
        <p>The article quotes an adware company executive as saying that the adware industry didn't talk to consumers ''about the benefits of software-based advertising'' and that it would be ''a battle to transcend the simplistic perception that most consumers have about adware.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Barbarians at the Digital Gate'' (Sept. 19), which described how pop-up ads and other interruptions were angering computer users:</p>
        <p>The article quotes an adware company executive as saying that the adware industry didn't talk to consumers ''about the benefits of software-based advertising'' and that it would be ''a battle to transcend the simplistic perception that most consumers have about adware.''</p>
        <p>What's wrong with my perception of adware? I perceive that it interrupts me when I'm trying to work, takes up space on my hard drive, occupies my computer's memory and ties up the C.P.U. -- all of which I pay for.</p>
        <p>In the United States there is a national ''do not call'' list to defend against intrusive telemarketing. What about the intrusions facing computer users?</p>
        <p>Christian Johansen  Ottawa, Sept. 20</p>
      </block>
